{
  "texts": [
    "A study reported 80% accuracy, thus establishing that multiclass classification is feasible even in very complex tissue images where cell morphology is highly heterogeneous.",
    "This approach is particularly appropriate to take advantage of the power of deep learning to assist pathologists in early and precise oral cancer detection, providing a reproducible and scalable alternative to manual scoring and reducing diagnostic variability.",
    "By focusing on multiclass cell-level classification, [5] Das et al. 's work is complementary to broader lesion-level classification research and is well-positioned to highlight the importance of automated, high-resolution analysis in oral cancer screening.",
    "[2] proposed an EfficientNet-based deep learning model for the detection of oral squamous cell carcinoma (OSCC) from histopathological images.",
    "The EfficientNet-B0 to B7 architectures were employed in the research to investigate morphological tissue features and compare their performance with traditional CNNs such as VGG16 and ResNet50."
  ]
}